<h2>Overview (TL;DR)</h2>

<p>Phreesia's patient check-in product included a pain scale questionnaire with a body diagram where patients could mark their pain location. Drop-off data showed 7% of patients were abandoning the check-in at this section — the highest drop-off point in the entire flow. An accessibility audit revealed the body diagram was completely unusable for keyboard-only and screen reader users: no tab stops, no text alternatives, no alternative path. The fix required navigating a business constraint that complicated the most straightforward solution, and researching a design pattern I hadn't used before. The result was a 3.4% reduction in drop-off, though gaps in our testing mean I can't fully stand behind the screen reader experience we shipped.</p>

<blockquote class="pull-quote" role="note">
  <p>"We didn't have a UI problem. We had an assumptions problem — and the assumptions had been baked in for three years."</p>
</blockquote>

<h2>Problem</h2>

<p>Seven percent of patients were abandoning the check-in at the pain scale section. That number came from limited data on an antiquated platform, but it was the highest drop-off point we could identify. Prior usability testing of the overall registration flow hadn't surfaced any obvious barriers. The pain scale section hadn't been part of that testing.</p>

<p>When I looked at the body diagram more closely, the problem was immediate. The component was an image with no keyboard interaction, no tab stops, and no meaningful text alternative. A screen reader announced the file name. That was it.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p class="callout__label">Key problem</p>
  <p>For any patient navigating with a keyboard or assistive technology, this was a complete barrier.</p>
</div>

<p>This hadn't been caught before because accessibility wasn't on the organisation's radar. Getting a fix prioritised required my PM to escalate to leadership — a conversation I wasn't part of, and wasn't certain would go the way I hoped.</p>

<h2>Process</h2>

<p>While the business case was being made internally, I started exploring what a fix might look like. My instinct was to change as little as possible on the front end: add tab stops to the existing image, write patient-friendly text alternatives for each region, and handle focus indication within the existing visual design. A more significant alternative — replacing the diagram with progressive dropdown lists — felt like too large a departure and would have created a meaningfully different experience for the patients who needed it most.</p>

<p>One constraint complicated this. The business wanted to keep the ability for patients to select a custom, specific point on the diagram, which they believed was clinically valuable. That ruled out the simplest accessible approach, because free-form point selection on an image is genuinely difficult to make keyboard-accessible. We couldn't do both in one unified interaction. That's what led me toward an accessibility mode toggle.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p class="callout__label">Key problem</p>
  <p>The accessible version couldn't do everything the original could. That was the constraint we couldn't design our way out of.</p>
</div>

<p>I wasn't comfortable with this at first. A separate mode felt like the kind of thing that gets deprioritised in future iterations and quietly breaks without anyone noticing. But I also knew I couldn't make that call based on my own assumptions — I needed to hear from people who actually use assistive technology. UserZoom's participant pool made this nearly impossible. The incidence rate for keyboard-only and screen reader users was under 1%. I managed one interview. That wasn't enough to go on.</p>

<p>So I took it to Reddit: r/accessibility, r/blind, r/webaccess, and r/assistivetechnology. It felt scrappy, but the alternative was proceeding without any validation at all. I disclosed I was a designer working on a healthcare product and asked directly how people felt about accessibility mode toggles. The response reframed my thinking. The consistent message was that accessibility mode doesn't create a separate experience — it changes how the interface is interacted with, not what the interface does. Respondents were comfortable with the pattern as long as the toggle was easy to find. I stopped thinking of it as a compromise.</p>

<p>From there, the decisions became more granular. Where should the toggle live? Proximity felt important — accessibility mode only affected the body diagram at this point, so placing it at the start of the full questionnaire felt disconnected. I put it at the top of the body diagram page. What should the label say? The goal was to set clear expectations rather than leave patients guessing. I wrote the initial options and worked with a copywriter to refine them. I made the final call.</p>

<p>Tab order and the number of focusable regions were decisions I deferred to a clinical information specialist I'd sought out earlier. Starting from over 100 potential regions, they made the final call on which 40 to include and how to label them. The specialist also raised something I hadn't considered: could the patient-facing label and the clinical label for each region be different? A patient hears "wrist," the EHR receives "carpal region." My architect confirmed this was possible — and unlike the custom-point diagram, this version would spare clinicians the step of interpreting a dot on an image. The accessible version was, in one specific way, more useful to them than what it was replacing.</p>

<p>For the focus indicator, the browser default rectangle wasn't sufficient on its own, but custom shapes for 40 body regions weren't feasible within our timeline. I designed the solution: default rectangle for the focus outline, with a colour-filled vector overlay on each region to make the active area visually clear. My architect confirmed it was feasible to build. I adjusted the focus indicator colour to meet contrast requirements.</p>

<p>I ran usability sessions with six keyboard-only users. The tab order was predictable. Knowing which region had focus was clear. Tab to navigate, Enter to select — intuitive. Two things weren't working: patients didn't immediately notice the accessibility toggle when they arrived on the page, and once they enabled it, it wasn't obvious what had changed. Given where we were in the timeline, I addressed these with targeted text instructions and a toast notification on toggle activation. They were lighter touches than I wanted. I knew that at the time.</p>

<h2>Solution</h2>

<p>The shipped solution added an accessibility mode toggle to the body diagram page. When enabled, patients could navigate approximately 40 labelled body regions using their keyboard, with a visible focus indicator and screen-reader-friendly text for each region. The custom point selection remained available for patients not using accessibility mode.</p>

<p>Drop-off at the pain scale section fell by 3.4%. Time spent on the section increased by more than 20 seconds on average — expected, given that keyboard navigation through 40 regions takes longer than tapping a point on an image. When PM leadership flagged the time increase, we'd already prepared the explanation. They accepted it.</p>

<p>The 3.4% reduction is meaningful but partial. The body diagram was one friction point in a multi-question section. We identified several others — the repetitive flow for multiple pain points, the ambiguity of some pain-type labels, the drag-versus-click ambiguity on the severity scale — that we didn't address in this release.</p>

