<h2>Reflection</h2>

<p>The decision I'd revisit most directly is the one to skip usability testing with screen reader users. The call was made on cost: we shared a credit pool across the team, and my manager and I agreed not to spend more on this project for the initial release. I understood the constraint. I still think we made the wrong call.</p>

<p>I was the only person who tested the screen reader experience, and I'm not a regular screen reader user. I tested with Safari and VoiceOver — I have no idea how the experience holds up with NVDA or JAWS, which are more widely used. Screen reader behaviour varies significantly across browser and assistive technology combinations, and those nuances aren't things I would reliably catch myself. Without that testing, we were essentially leaving it to real patients to find the gaps. That's not a QA process. That's just shipping and hoping.</p>

<p>If I were doing this again, I'd push harder for screen reader testing as a condition of release, not a nice-to-have. The cost was real. But so was the risk of spending significant time and effort on an accessibility fix that didn't actually work for the people it was meant to serve.</p>
